Democracy without popular cohesion
Something has happened to democracy in the sense that the government is elected by the people and this happens all over the world.
Somehow, people have lost faith in elections.
Voter turnout is declining in many countries; in the case of European Parliament elections, the voter turnout was so low that the legitimacy of the election result is questionable.
Beyond voter turnout, we have gotten used to accepting parties or candidates who receive 25% of the votes as "winners".
From Holland to Finland, and on to Argentina and Japan, majority governments are formed based on minorities.
Even the apparent exceptions do not prove the opposite.
Only a few American presidents were elected by more than 10% of eligible voters. In fact, half of eligible voters in the US did not even register to vote; of those who registered, half did not vote; and of those who did vote, less than half voted for the winner.
Even Tony Blair's "landslide" majority in the UK House of Commons stands on shaky ground: the Labour Party received only slightly over 40% of the votes in the last election in 2002, with a voter turnout of 60%.
Thus, only 24% of the total electorate supported Blair's party.
In most countries, elections look very different today than they did just twenty, or even fifty years ago.
What has happened?
A possible answer is that voters mistrust political parties.
Electoral democracy works in most countries through organizations that put forward candidates who advocate for certain packages of political options, known as a "manifesto" or "election program."
For a number of reasons, this time-tested practice no longer functions.
Ideological party programs have lost their power; voters no longer accept the packages imposed by the parties, they want to grab something for themselves and choose.
Furthermore, political parties have become machines composed of tightly organized cliques of insiders.
The paradox here is that parties, having lost their specific ideological orientation, have become even more cliquey.
It is more important to belong to them than to share their specific beliefs.
Such developments have alienated the parties from the voters.
Because most people do not want to belong to any particular party, only a minority plays the party game anymore.
This also increases public suspicion towards political parties, especially since, like in professional sports, it is expensive to participate – and when taxpayers foot the bill, it is taken very badly.
If the costs are borne by taxpayers, it is harshly criticized.
But without financial support from the state, the parties would have to obtain money through channels that are often questionable, if not outright illegal.
Many of the major political scandals of recent decades involved the financing of parties and their candidates.
Other indications - such as the clear decline in memberships - confirm that parties have become unpopular.
Nevertheless, parties are indispensable for an electoral democracy.
The result is an obvious separation between visible political actors and the electorate.
Since parties are active in parliaments, the effects of this separation affect one of the key institutions of democracy.
People no longer believe that parliaments represent them and therefore do not possess the necessary legitimacy to make decisions on their behalf.
At this point, another fairly independent development comes into play.
People today are more impatient than ever before.
As consumers, they are accustomed to immediate satisfaction.
But as voters, they have to wait before they can feel the results of the election they cast at the ballot box.
Sometimes they never see the desired results.
Democracy needs time not only for elections but also for discussions and prudent weighing.
However, the voter as consumer does not want to accept this and therefore turns away.
There are alternatives. But each has its own problems as a democratic solution.
"Direct Action" through demonstrations has become a regular and often effective event.
For less mobile people, it could be replaced by the possibility of expressing their opinion electronically; this ranges from internet chat pages to electronic messages to political leaders.
Then there are non-governmental organizations. They often have undemocratic structures, yet seem more closely connected to citizens.
In addition, there is always the option to completely opt out and leave politics to the experts, focusing instead on other aspects of life.
This latter option likely carries the greatest risks, as it fosters creeping authoritarianism, which is a hallmark of our time.
But even the other signs of separation between politics and citizens create a rather uncertain state of affairs, as no one can say anymore how representative the prevailing views are.
Some want to address the knot through more direct democracy.
But maintaining a connection between leaders and followers cannot be achieved by reducing public debate to simple voting alternatives.
There is still much to be said for holding on to the classical institutions of parliamentary democracy and trying to reconnect them more closely with the citizenry.
Unpopular parties and declining voter turnout could turn out to be only temporary phenomena.
New parties could emerge and infuse elections and representative governments with more life.
But this probably would not be enough to restore the general legitimacy that elected governments have lost.
Therefore, the first concern for all who care about freedom must be to reimagine democracy and its institutions.
